<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hubei Farmers Prosper From Breeding Aquatic Products </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2802040794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0225 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2802040794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Wuhan, February 28 (XINHUA) -- Breeding of aquatic 
products is now an important way to become prosperous for 
farmers from central China's Hubei Province. 
  Statistics show that last year farmers engaged in breeding 
of 
aquatic products achieved a per capita net income of 1,100 yuan, 
300 yuan more than the corresponding figure for those farmers 
not engaged in cultivation of such products. 
  Hubei, known to have a thousand lakes and dubbed as a "land 
of fish and rice", has a water area of 1.33 million hectares, of 
which more than 400,000 hectares have been used for breeding of 
aquatic products of various kinds. 
  According to Che Guangbiao, director of the Hubei Provincial 
Bureau of Aquatic Products, over the past 15 years output of 
aquatic products of the province has increased by 50,000 tons a 
year. 
  The output of aquatic products for 1993 surpassed one 
million 
tons, and the per capita availability of fresh water fish 
reached 16 kg in the province, ranking second in the country. 
  Local officials attributed the quick development of the 
breeding sector to reform in circulation of aquatic products and 
the application of scientific methods in their cultivation. 
  Thanks to the reform in circulation of aquatic products, 
traders representing different ownerships have all moved in to 
engage in the aquatic products trade, effectively solving the 
difficulty for growers of aquatic products in selling their 
products. 
  A dozen scientific research institutes in Wuhan City, the 
provincial capital, boast more than 2,000 senior experts of 
aquatic products. 
  Besides giving technical guidance to local farmers, 
researchers with these institutes have developed bait for young 
salmon and the artificial propagation of river crabs, as well as 
introduced approximately 40 new varieties of fish from abroad. 
The efforts have brought about great economic returns. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

