<F P=100> North Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hebei Reports Record Grain Harvest in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2402183694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1441 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402183694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Shijiazhuang, February 24 (XINHUA) -- North China's 
Hebei Province, one of China's important agricultural bases, has 
reported an all-time record harvest of grain last year despite 
harsh arid conditions. 
  The total grain output of the province hit some 23.8 million 
tons last year, one million tons more than that in 1990, which 
was the previous record, according to the latest official 
statistics. 
  Meanwhile, the total agricultural output value of Hebei in 
1993 topped some 50.1 billion yuan, up 6.2 percent from the 
previous year. 
  Exceptionally serious dry weather attacked most of the area 
over the past year. The average rainfall in the first half of 
1993 dropped to only some ten millimeters per month, official 
sources said. 
  In addition, water in most of the reservoirs and canals 
dried 
up due to rare drought. 
  To fight the drought, the provincial government collected 
some 500 million yuan to construct irrigation systems, draw 
water and readjust the crop structure. 
  With the support of local governments, the Hebei people sank 
about 780,000 pump wells, and the total area of effectively 
irrigated farmland reached some 3.93 million ha [hectares]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-1649 </DOCNO>
