<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lu Ping Says British Try To `Mislead' Public </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK2702070594 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in Chinese 1200 GMT 
26 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2702070594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporters You Xiayin (3266 1115 5419) and Gan Zhebin </F>
(3927 0772 2430): "Lu Ping, State Council Hong Kong and Macao 
Affairs Office Director, Indicates That for the British To 
Spread the Idea That Hong Kong's Government Structure Will Not 
Terminate After 1997 Is To Mislead Public Opinion"] 
  [Text] Beijing, 26 Feb (ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE) -- Lu Ping, 
director of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office of the State 
Council, noted here today that the British side is trying to 
mislead Hong Kong people by spreading the view that the 
three-tier constitutional framework the British Hong Kong 
Government is going to set up will not be terminated after 1 
July 1997. 
  In response to a question raised by a reporter in a special 
television program today, Lu Ping said: Britain's publication 
of a white paper to unilaterally give its account of the 
Sino-British talks on the Hong Kong constitutional system 
indicates that the British side, on the one hand, is adopting a 
non-cooperative attitude toward China in the coming three and a 
half years, and on the other hand, is trying to make the 
three-tier councils established on the basis of its own 
constitutional reform package a fait accompli. 
  Lu Ping pointed out: The British Hong Kong Government's 
three-tier councils are bound to be short-lived. District 
boards, the Urban Council, and the Regional Council, as well as 
the Legislative Council, all will be terminated on 30 June 1997. 
We hope the British side will no longer indulge in any illusion 
in this regard. Lu Ping reiterated that China always means what 
it says, so by 1 July 1997 China surely will "set up another 
stove" in accordance with the provisions of the Basic Law. 
  Talking about the progress the Chinese side has made so far 
in "setting up another stove" under the present circumstance, Lu 
Ping said: The Preliminary Work Committee [PWC] of the 
Preparatory Committee for the Hong Kong Special Administration 
Region must step up its operation. The members of the PWC all 
feel the heavy workload, and they unanimously agree to speed up 
the working pace of the PWC. As for the "stove," the design of 
it is already there in the Basic Law. Our task now is to set up 
the "stove" by 1 July 1997 following the design laid out in the 
Basic Law. And what the PWC is going to do is to implement 
properly the provisions in the Basic Law, and to strive to 
ensure a steady transition and to maintainthe prosperity and 
stability of Hong Kong through 1997, given Britain's policy of 
non-cooperation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-1667 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi039_w_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-039 </AU>
