<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhu Rongji Meets Japanese Economic Figures, Officials </TI></H3>
<H4>   Urges Technology Transfer </H4>
<F P=102> OW2502153194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1516 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2502153194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, February 25 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Vice Premier 
Zhu Rongji today urged Japanese firms to increase their 
technology transfer to China to help it modernize the country. 
  "My answer is very clear: I want Japan to give us more 
technology," Zhu replied to a question during a press conference 
at the Japan National Press Club in Tokyo. 
  He said he was pleased that a rising number of Japanese 
corporations had began to give know-how to their Chinese 
partners while doing trade with them. 
  Japan ranked first in the transfer of foreign technology to 
China last year, in which 28 percent of China's technology 
imports came from Japan, he noted. 
  "It's great. It will eventually benefit Japan's economic 
development," he added. 
  The advancement of Chinese technology will help upgrade the 
competitiveness of Japanese products on the international market 
since most of the transfer were done through Japan's joint 
ventures with China there, the vice premier explained. 
  Zhu, who is in Tokyo on a nine-day visit, cited as a model 
of 
bilateral technology cooperation the start of videorecorder 
production in Beijing last year with full technology given by 
Matsushita, a Japanese electronics giant. 
  He hoped that more Japanese makers will follow Matsushita in 
doing so. 
  Zhu underlined the importance of Japanese support for 
China's 
reform and economic development and vowed to work hard to boost 
Beijing's ties with Tokyo. 
  He said he felt satisfied over recent years' "marked 
progress" in bilateral trade, which totaled 39 billion U.S. 
dollars in 1993, an increase of 54 percent over the previous 
year. 
  But he said this is still short of its potential in view of 
the present good relationship between the two countries. 
  Japan overtook Hong Kong as China's biggest trading partner 
while China became Japan's second largest trading partner after 
the United States in 1993. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

