<F P=100> Southeast Asia &amp; Pacific </F>
<H3> <TI>   Singapore's Lee Kuan Yew, Delegation Visit Tianjin </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2402195494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1456 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402195494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tianjin, February 24 (XINHUA) -- Gao Dezhan, 
secretary of the Chinese Communist Party Tianjin Municipal 
Committee, and Zhang Lichang, mayor of Tianjin, met here today 
with Lee Kuan Yew, Singaporean senior minister. 
  Lee and his party arrived here this afternoon. This is his 
first Tianjin visit. 
  During the meeting, Gao said that the investment environment 
in this biggest industrial city in north China is very good, and 
the fields for foreign investment are broad. 
  He expressed his hope that Tianjin would further its 
economic 
cooperation with Singapore. 
  Lee said that the expressway linking Beijing and Tianjin has 
brought the city closer to China's capital, thus giving impetus 
to its development. Singapore will help Tianjin's economy 
through making investment here. 
  His advance party, a Singaporean industrial and commercial 
observation group, consisting of officials of some governmental 
departments and heads of large-sized enterprises, arrived here 
yesterday. 
  Lee and his party, during their visit here, will observe 
Tianjin's investment environment and hold talks concerning 
cooperation in fields of economy and trade, science and 
technology and urban construction. 
  The Singaporean businessmen today started their talks with 
their Chinese counterparts here about cooperation in areas such 
as real estate development, building materials production and 
port construction. Agreements on a number of cooperative 
projects and joint ventures were signed today. 
  By the end of last year, 148 enterprises had been set up in 
the city by Singaporean businessmen, according to the city's 
foreign economic and trade committee. 
  The contracted volume of investment by these enterprises has 
reached 178 million U.S. dollars, which ranks 6th among 77 
countries and regions investing in Tianjin. 

</TEXT>

