<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   First Round of Trade Talks With U.S. Concludes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2802043794 Taipei China Broadcasting Corporation News 
Network in Mandarin 2300 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2802043794 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei China Broadcasting Corporation News 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Mandarin </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Hookup" program] </F>
  [Text] A first round of bilateral trade talks between the 
ROC [Republic of China] and the United States on the former's 
admission to GATT has ended for the time being. 
  People have been most concerned with issues of tariff 
reduction in agricultural products. Even though they failed to 
respond completely to the U.S.-proposed list of 387 agricultural 
products earmarked for tariff reduction, the ROC has agreed to 
reduce tariffs on 277 items. The tariff reduction rates will be 
more than 20 percent. 
  It has been learned that, under strong U.S. pressure, tariff 
reductions on imported apples will be the largest. Tariff 
reductions on certain sensitive agricultural products, including 
fresh pears, peaches, plums, and processed fruit juices, will be 
relatively low and will be reduced gradually over six years in 
order to lessen their adverse impact. 
  The Council of Agriculture indicated: To counterbalance 
future massive tariff reductions on agricultural products -- 
especially imported fruits including apples, whose imported 
quantity is large -- and fresh fruits that are produced by major 
exporting countries at low production costs, the ROC will shift 
from the existing practice of levying tariffs on fresh fruits in 
accordance with their price levels to a new practice of levying 
tariffs in accordance with their imported quantities, or levying 
mixed tariffs by integrating the existing and new practices. 
The ROC has formally notified the U.S. delegation that we are 
shifting from the existing practice to a new practice of levying 
tariffs on fresh fruits. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

