<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serb Spokesman Says 4 Downed Planes Not Serbian </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2802164894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1628 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2802164894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, February 28 (XINHUA) -- A Serb military 
spokesman said today that the four warplanes shot down by NATO 
fighter jets did not belong to the Serbian Air Forces. 
  Nebojsha Radmanovich, spokesman for the Serb military press 
center in Banja Luka, near where the four planes were downed, 
said that Serb planes did not fly today. 
  NATO said two U.S. F-16 fighters first warned and then shot 
down four Galeb light attack aircraft early this morning near 
Banja Luka, the main Serb air base in northern Bosnia. 
  This was the first Western military intervention in the 
22-month-long conflict, and NATO's first combat action since it 
was founded in 1949. 
  U.N. sources in Zagreb said the Serb planes had apparently 
attacked a Muslim-controlled ammunition factory in central 
Bosnia shortly before being shot down. 
  Muslim radio in Sarajevo also reported that Serb planes this 
morning attacked Muslim targets in central Bosnia. 
  But Serb military personnel said all their warplanes were 
under the supervision of United Nations observers, and that if 
the planes took off they could not escape detection by the 
observers. 
  NATO jets have flown more than 1,000 sorties over 
Bosnia-Herzegovina since last April when the no-fly zone 
injunction took effect. 
  NATO said it will continue to take military action against 
any plane that intrudes into the no-fly zone. 

</TEXT>

