<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Zealand Backs NATO's Shooting Down of Serb Jets </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0103082594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0711 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0103082594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Wellington, March 1 (XINHUA) -- New Zealand today 
voiced its backing for NATO's action yesterday in shooting down 
four military planes said to be flown by Bosnian Serbs. 
  Foreign Minister Don McKinnon said NATO was acting within 
the 
mandate of the Security Council resolution passed last March 
when New Zealand acted as president. 
  "They (the aircraft) were warned, they ignored it and they 
have paid the price," he said. 
  "The resolution really sent two signals -- that the Security 
Council would not tolerate violations of its resolutions and 
decisions and that the best course was to stop fighting and 
instead work on setting differences by negotiation," the 
minister added. 
  NATO said its fighters yesterday shot down four Serb 
warplanes which were conducting a bombing raid over Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

