<H3> <TI>   Spanish Premier Approves NATO Air Attack </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0103044394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0407 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0103044394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Madrid, February 28 (XINHUA) -- Spanish Prime 
Minister Felipe Gonzalez expressed his approval here today after 
U.S.-piloted jets shot down four Serbian warplanes, but he 
warned against reoccurrence of such action. 
  The incident should not repeat itself, Gonzalez said, adding 
that a tense atmosphere would undermine the budding hope of a 
long-waited peace in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The prime minister noted that the incident indicated the UN 
ban on air flights over Bosnia ought not to be violated. "In 
fact, the air attack is in strictly keeping with the resolution 
of the UN Security Council," he said. 
  Spanish Foreign Minister Javier Solana also attributed 
NATO's 
air attack to Serbs' violation of the no-fly zone and emphasized 
that it should not undermine the favorable turn resulting from 
the lifting of the siege in Sarajevo. 
  The attack occurred today as American pilots saw "bombing 
maneuvers" of the planes and explosions on the ground. One 
American F-16 fighter jet shot down three planes and a second 
downed a fourth. 
  It was the first time NATO used its military might in the 
23-month-old Bosnia war and its 44-year history. 

</TEXT>

