<H3> <TI>   Australia Urges Continuance of Bosnia Peace Process </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0103083694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0715 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0103083694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Canberra, March 1 (XINHUA) -- Australian Foreign 
Minister Gareth Evans today urged all parties in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina to "press ahead urgently with the peace 
process". 
  The war-torn nation needs a negotiated settlement to end the 
tragic conflict, Evans said in a statement after U.S. planes 
shot down four military aircraft in Bosnia yesterday. 
  He regarded the action as "in strict accordance with the 
provisions of the U.N.-imposed no fly zone in Bosnia". 
  Meanwhile, he called upon all parties concerned in the 
country not to take any retaliatory action against the U.N. 
Forces or international relief efforts. 
  "It is essential that the humanitarian effort be allowed to 
continue uninterrupted and that the current momentum for 
restoring peace in Bosnia-Herzegovina continue," Evans said. 

</TEXT>

