<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Russia's Expulsion of U.S. Diplomat </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2802220494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1828 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2802220494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, February 28 (XINHUA) -- Russia today 
declared U.S. diplomat James Morris "persona non grata" and 
urged him to leave the country within seven days in retaliation 
for the recent expulsion of a Russian diplomat by Washington. 
  In a statement to the U.S. Embassy, the Russian Foreign 
Ministry accused Morris, who works as a counselor at the U.S. 
Embassy in Moscow, of engaging in activities incompatible with 
his diplomatic status, noting him as an agent of the U.S. 
Central Intelligence Agency (CIA). 
  "The Russian Foreign Ministry is lodging a protest against 
illegal activities of the American side with regard to an 
official representative of the Russian Foreign Intelligence 
Service who has been working in Washington since the summer of 
1993 by mutual consent," the statement said. 
  "In this situation," the statement continued, "we have to 
declare, on the basis of reciprocity, a CIA officer in Moscow 
persona non grata and demand that he leave the Russian 
Federation." 
  It also said that "The Russian Foreign Ministry proceeds 
from 
the fact that there are special channels for settling issues 
arising on both sides in connection with intelligence or 
counterintelligence activity. The channels can and should be 
engaged. This will allow (us) to find a mutually acceptable way 
out from the current situation and avoid its politicization." 
  On Friday [25 February], the United States declared Russian 
diplomat Aleksandr Lysenko persona non grata and ordered him to 
leave the country within seven days. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

