<H3> <TI>   U.S. Says Russian Expulsion of Diplomat Unjustified </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0103040594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0306 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0103040594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, February 28 (XINHUA) -- The United 
States today protested in the strongest possible terms at the 
expulsion from Russia of a U.S. Embassy officer, describing it 
as an unjustified retaliation to its own actions over Russian 
spies. 
  U.S. State Department spokesman Mike McCurry said the 
expulsion of a Russian resident from the United States on Friday 
[25 February] was entirely justified. 
  He was referring to the the espionage case of former CIA 
counter- intelligence officer Aldrich Ames, who the U.S. alleges 
had been a long-term underground member of the Russian 
intelligence service. 
  "By contrast," McCurry said, "the expulsion of the U.S. 
diplomat from Moscow is purely an act of unjustified 
retaliation." 
  He reiterated that Washington reserves the right to take 
further action if there are others implicated in connection with 
the case of Ames, who was allegedly paid more than 1.5 million 
dollars for collecting vital CIA operational and personnel 
information for Moscow. 
  "We will continue to assess, as that investigation and 
prosecution develops, what further measures might be necessary," 
McCurry added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

