<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Notes U.S.-SRV Talks on Compensation, Offices </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2802212794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1230 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2802212794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hanoi, February 28 (XINHUA) -- Vietnam and the 
United States today began talks on compensation for properties 
confiscated by both sides after 1975, the year of Vietnam's 
reunification. 
  Nguyen Xuan Phong, acting director of American affairs in 
the 
Foreign Ministry of Vietnam and head of the Vietnamese 
delegation, told reporters that the U.S. Government should make 
a comprehensive account of former South Vietnam Government 
properties which were frozen by the U.S. after 1975. 
  The U.S. delegation is headed by James Hall of the East Asia 
and Pacific Affairs Bureau of the U.S. State Department. 
  The Vietnamese Government estimates the worth of the frozen 
properties of former South Vietnam at around 250 million U.S. 
dollars. 
  The U.S. attorney general has received 192 requests from 
U.S. 
companies and individuals asking the government to seek 
compensation of around 230 million dollars from Vietnam. 
  The two sides will also work out a detailed schedule for 
setting up liaison offices in each other's capital, as agreed 
upon following the lifting of U.S. economic sanctions against 
Vietnam in early February. 

</TEXT>

