<F P=100> Northeast Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   World Bank Loan To Aid Liaoning, Jilin Farmers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2502224394 Beijing XINHUA in English 2125 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2502224394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, February 25 (XINHUA) -- The World Bank 
announced today it has approved a loan of 205 million U.S. 
dollars to help the poor farm families in China's northeastern 
province of Liaoning and Jilin. 
  The loan, through the International Development Association, 
will support the Songliao Plain agricultural development 
project, which will cost a total of 382.3 million dollars, the 
World Bank said. 
  Most families in the project area have an annual income of 
about 140 dollars. "They are constrained by single crop 
production, low productivity, and an uncertain market for the 
crop," said project manager Rapeepun Jaisaard. 
  The project, the official said, will increase the amount of 
available farmland and overall productivity by reclaiming 
currently unarable land and expanding irrigation on already 
farmed land. 
  About 6,200 hectares of saline-alkaline wasteland in 
Liaoning 
Province will be reclaimed under the project. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

