<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Southwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Guizhou Treats Victims of Arsenic Poisoning Free </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2402130794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0842 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402130794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guiyang, February 24 (XINHUA) -- People suffering 
from arsenic poisoning owing to the burning of arsenic-bearing 
coal in Guizhou Province, south-west China, are receiving good 
treatment, according to local officials. 
  The first cases of arsenic poisoning were discovered in 1991 
in one of Guizhou's Prefectures inhabited by ethnic minority 
people, and so far 1,908 victims have been diagnosed in the 
province. 
  During the past three years the Guizhou Provincial 
Government 
has allocated 288,000 yuan to treat 1,696 such patients free of 
charge. Most of them are recovering well. 
  This year the government will set aside another 500,000 yuan 
for its treatment program. 
  Relevant government departments have also made comprehensive 
surveys of the coal mines to close down those producing coal 
with too high an arsenic content, to prevent any further arsenic 
poisoning. 

</TEXT>

