<F P=101> Southwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yunnan Broadcasts Family Planning Programs for Minorities </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2102113094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1119 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2102113094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kunming, February 21 (XINHUA) -- Yunnan People's 
Broadcasting Station has started sending out family planning 
programs in five languages of minority nationalities. 
  The five-tongue programs take up eight hours a day. They 
include the languages of the Dai nationality in Dehong 
Prefecture and Xishuangbanna Prefecture, Jingpo nationality, 
Lahu nationality and Lisu nationality. 
  Yunnan Province has 25 minority nationalities, with 12.34 
million people, accounting for one third of the total population. 
  Since the 1970s, the minority nationalities in Yunnan 
Province have come to realize the connection between raising the 
quality of life and carrying out family planning policies. 
  According to the fourth national census in 1990, in the 
eight 
years from 1982 to 1990, the growth rate of the minority 
nationalities in the country was 34.8 percent, but the rate in 
Yunnan Province was about 19.6 percent. 
  Dong Xiuying, a chief editor at the Department of Minority 
Nationalities of Yunnan broadcasting station, who is herself 
from the minority Va nationality, said that many of the ethnic 
people do not understand the Han language and it was necessary 
to start broadcasting these programs in their own languages. 
  There are eight autonomous prefectures of minority 
nationalities in Yunnan. The broadcasting stations in four of 
the prefectures, including Dehong, Xishuangbanna, Nujiang and 
Diqing, also started ethnic language programs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

