<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agriculture </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zou Jiahua, Li Lanqing Attend Enterprise Reform Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2802212094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1528 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2802212094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 28 (XINHUA) -- Vice-Premier Zou 
Jiahua said here today that China's reforms will be promoted if 
the large and medium-sized state enterprises carry out the 
central government's reform scheme in an exemplary way. 
  At a meeting with the managers of 40 large state enterprises 
from all over the country, Zou urged the managers to set great 
store by study which involves Deng Xiaoping's theory of building 
socialism with Chinese characteristics, new laws and 
regulations, new policies and new technology. 
  He said that at present the State Council was selecting 100 
enterprises for pioneering the reforms. 
  He noted that the new measures for the reforms adopted by 
the 
government aim at helping the state enterprises transform their 
operating system, enabling the enterprises to take part in 
market competition. 
  The 40 managers are attending a forum which opened on 
February 22, jointly sponsored by the Organization Department of 
the Central Committee of the Chinese Communist Party and the 
State Economic and Trade Commission. 
  Vice-Premier Li Lanqing presided over the meeting. 

</TEXT>

