<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agriculture </F>
<H3> <TI>   Investment in Fixed Assets Grows in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2802145894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1346 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2802145894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing February 28 (XINHUA) -- China completed 
1,182.9 billion yuan (203.9 billion U.S. dollars then) of 
investment in fixed assets last year, 50.6 percent up over 1992, 
or a real growth of 22 percent after inflation. 
  This was revealed by Zhang Sai, head of the State Statistics 
Bureau (SSB), at a press conference today. 
  He said that state-owned enterprises invested 464.7 billion 
yuan in capital construction last year, representing a 54.2 
percent increase over 1992; investment in real estate for sale 
totalled 113.8 billion yuan, registering a 124.9 percent 
increase over the year before, and in other projects, 34.4 
billion yuan, up 17 percent. 
  The service industry had the most conspicuous increase in 
investment -- to 317.5 billion yuan -- by state-owned 
enterprises, said the official, noting its share surged from 
38.3 percent to 44.3 percent. 
  Investment in transport, postal and telecommunications 
facilities shared 20 percent of the total last year, up from 
14.7 percent in 1992, he said. 
  Zhang told the press that the newly increased production 
capacity in 1993 through capital construction projects included: 
eight million tons of coal mining, 14.38 million kilowatts of 
power generation, 15.43 million tons of oil extraction and 1 
billion cubic meters of natural gas. 
  Some 274 kilometers of railway tracks and 3,556 kilometers 
of 
highways were built, 37.52 million tons of cargo-handling 
capacity of coastal harbors were finished, he added. 
  In addition, other production and transportation capacities 
of iron, timber, cement were remarkably enhanced last year 
through the increased investment in fixed assets, the official 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

